And that's fine, like that happens.

48
00:03:29,987 --> 00:03:33,309
But I was a lot more raw coming out of that

49
00:03:33,630 --> 00:03:35,051
than I really needed to be.

50
00:03:35,431 --> 00:03:37,232
And that dramatically affected

51
00:03:37,332 --> 00:03:39,634
the next six months of my life.

52
00:03:40,814 --> 00:03:42,856
And I also wrote some stuff on the internet,

53
00:03:43,376 --> 00:03:46,899
which was maybe a little more spicy than it needed to be.

54
00:03:48,320 --> 00:03:50,321
But now 210,000 people have read it.

55
00:03:50,401 --> 00:03:51,762
So that's kind of a little too late

56
00:03:51,802 --> 00:03:53,263
to put the genie back in the bottle.

57
00:03:55,309 --> 00:03:56,890
But yeah, so why did I feel so burned?

58
00:03:58,851 --> 00:04:01,852
I did, and accidentally, there were just a lot of things.

59
00:04:02,192 --> 00:04:03,533
It was my first time shipping a game,

60
00:04:03,613 --> 00:04:05,374
and my first time really committing

61
00:04:05,494 --> 00:04:09,135
to an experience of that kind of magnitude.

62
00:04:09,155 --> 00:04:12,237
I mean, the only other thing really commensurate to game dev,

63
00:04:12,257 --> 00:04:13,517
especially when you're young.

64
00:04:13,697 --> 00:04:14,798
We started working on Brigador when I was 23.

65
00:04:14,938 --> 00:04:18,259
It was like going through college,

66
00:04:18,719 --> 00:04:22,601
and there's other things to help relax you on that.

67
00:04:24,773 --> 00:04:27,116
So one of the biggest things is expectation versus reality.

68
00:04:29,559 --> 00:04:35,306
And for me, there was a huge gap between what I expected

69
00:04:35,466 --> 00:04:38,230
for the launch of Brigador and what the reality was.

70
00:04:40,490 --> 00:04:44,054
It's natural for, though, there to be a disparity there.

71
00:04:45,215 --> 00:04:47,397
And one of the kind of frustrating ironies

72
00:04:47,597 --> 00:04:49,960
of being a more experienced developer

73
00:04:50,200 --> 00:04:54,185
is that you learn to better attune yourself to,

74
00:04:54,725 --> 00:04:58,009
like, attune those expectations to what is likely to happen.

75
00:04:59,839 --> 00:05:02,000
But what ends up happening is that at some point,

76
00:05:02,100 --> 00:05:03,841
there's a moment of reckoning.

77
00:05:04,802 --> 00:05:07,723
Or maybe if you're lucky, like a period of time

78
00:05:07,903 --> 00:05:10,764
in which those two things come together.

79
00:05:12,165 --> 00:05:14,166
And if that happens very quickly,

80
00:05:14,286 --> 00:05:15,887
like with a game launch when you have

81
00:05:15,907 --> 00:05:17,528
this kind of catastrophic realization

82
00:05:17,588 --> 00:05:23,711
that I've made a huge mistake, then that can be very jarring.

83
00:05:24,871 --> 00:05:25,371
Ideally.

84
00:05:27,169 --> 00:05:31,873
Making that shift should be either it's a small shift

85
00:05:32,113 --> 00:05:33,655
and it's going to be a soft experience

86
00:05:34,996 --> 00:05:39,039
or you have enough time to gradually bridge the gap.

87
00:05:39,379 --> 00:05:41,461
What happened to me in 2016 was more something like this.

88
00:05:45,995 --> 00:05:49,136
So there's actually a great film called 500 Days of Summer.

89
00:05:51,137 --> 00:05:54,157
And it's a great movie on the whole,

90
00:05:54,197 --> 00:05:57,898
but there's also a segment that's a few minutes long

91
00:05:58,498 --> 00:06:05,000
that I think very succinctly just describes and illustrates

92
00:06:05,080 --> 00:06:07,661
not only the difference there, but the impact

93
00:06:07,701 --> 00:06:08,521
that that can have.

94
00:06:12,006 --> 00:06:15,008
The caveat here is that it's not that we shouldn't just

95
00:06:15,088 --> 00:06:16,369
lower our expectations.

96
00:06:16,829 --> 00:06:18,430
I'm not telling anyone to do that.

97
00:06:19,831 --> 00:06:22,973
But I think there's kind of a third step you can add,

98
00:06:23,053 --> 00:06:26,375
which is aspiration versus expectation versus reality.

99
00:06:26,835 --> 00:06:28,276
We can aspire to be the best.

100
00:06:28,756 --> 00:06:31,998
And there's nothing wrong with striving for that.

101
00:06:32,599 --> 00:06:35,981
But you need that kind of middle ground of, OK,

102
00:06:36,401 --> 00:06:37,302
what's actually going to happen?

103
00:06:37,322 --> 00:06:38,943
Because if you don't protect yourself with that,

104
00:06:39,543 --> 00:06:45,149
then you can end up with this kind of whiplash that happens

105
00:06:45,169 --> 00:06:46,590
when you have to reconcile those things.

106
00:06:48,838 --> 00:06:54,423
So the second thing that I did was that I, because I put everything into the launch,

107
00:06:55,504 --> 00:07:00,829
and I sort of just assumed that things were going to go well enough that I would be fine,

108
00:07:01,209 --> 00:07:05,072
when it didn't, I had nothing left in the tank to help cope with the failure.

109
00:07:05,213 --> 00:07:10,057
So I was just sort of stuck in this awkward situation afterwards.

110
00:07:11,738 --> 00:07:12,699
And I wasn't...

111
00:07:15,399 --> 00:07:22,765
I got into this cycle where any time I was getting into any kind of recovery, any energy

112
00:07:22,785 --> 00:07:28,689
that I was getting back, any joie de vivre, was immediately spent on working on the game.

113
00:07:28,849 --> 00:07:34,233
So as soon as I got any of that back, I would burn real hard for like a day or a week or

114
00:07:34,273 --> 00:07:37,235
a month or like however long that I had that juice going for.

115
00:07:37,255 --> 00:07:41,198
And then I would put myself right back to where I was the day after that launch.

116
00:07:44,016 --> 00:07:47,037
And the third thing is that I was,

117
00:07:48,558 --> 00:07:50,198
you know, we talk about, you know,

118
00:07:50,258 --> 00:07:52,019
burnout and crunch and a lot of these things.

119
00:07:54,260 --> 00:07:57,121
It's different to be faced with that yourself

120
00:07:57,421 --> 00:08:00,062
and then to have to actually acknowledge

121
00:08:00,102 --> 00:08:03,263
that, you know, I'm not able to work

122
00:08:03,423 --> 00:08:07,965
or, you know, to continue at this level of performance

123
00:08:07,985 --> 00:08:09,845
that I had been going on for a while.

124
00:08:11,246 --> 00:08:14,647
Because it's kind of a frustrating thing to admit.

125
00:08:15,747 --> 00:08:18,467
And in that period afterward, I was like,

126
00:08:18,768 --> 00:08:19,868
I'm just going to keep working the way

127
00:08:19,888 --> 00:08:21,228
I have been for the last couple years.

128
00:08:22,088 --> 00:08:25,709
And I couldn't accept that it's just so OK to have a hard time.

129
00:08:26,909 --> 00:08:29,090
You need to have that kind of down period

130
00:08:29,590 --> 00:08:33,031
where if you go through an experience like a really

131
00:08:33,071 --> 00:08:36,071
bad launch that you spent five years on,

132
00:08:37,972 --> 00:08:40,914
there's gonna be, like you need time for that fallout

133
00:08:40,934 --> 00:08:44,037
to settle and to give yourself a chance to recover.

134
00:08:45,779 --> 00:08:47,000
When you go through an experience like that,

135
00:08:47,020 --> 00:08:49,342
you have two jobs, which is to get better,

136
00:08:49,362 --> 00:08:52,025
and it was what I described with

137
00:08:52,445 --> 00:08:54,147
don't like immediately burn yourself back out,

138
00:08:54,487 --> 00:08:56,008
and also don't make things worse.

139
00:08:57,699 --> 00:09:00,981
I got real close with that post that I showed earlier.

140
00:09:01,482 --> 00:09:04,304
If that had been tonally a little bit different, or maybe

141
00:09:04,364 --> 00:09:06,706
under different circumstances, that could have totally blown

142
00:09:06,787 --> 00:09:10,089
up in a bad way.

143
00:09:10,710 --> 00:09:11,731
It worked out OK for me.

144
00:09:14,207 --> 00:09:16,709
you know, don't, this kind of stuff feels real good,

145
00:09:18,111 --> 00:09:22,235
but that impulse is, you have to be very careful about.

146
00:09:22,255 --> 00:09:25,899
The one time I think I did handle it much better

