00:10:22,289 --> 00:10:29,732
And I know people say that like any press is good press, but I think there's a line there.

165
00:10:34,415 --> 00:10:39,397
So a final point is that this sort of relation of time to distance to understanding.

166
00:10:39,658 --> 00:10:43,740
So one of the...

167
00:10:46,556 --> 00:10:54,443
It wasn't until basically six months after our 1.0 launch in summer 2016 that I actually

168
00:10:55,304 --> 00:11:03,531
calmed down and got enough perspective on what had happened to actually start doing

169
00:11:03,592 --> 00:11:07,055
something about it, to start addressing it properly, both from a...

170
00:11:07,955 --> 00:11:10,237
dev side and also from a personal side.

171
00:11:11,058 --> 00:11:12,239
There's the classic phrase,

172
00:11:12,279 --> 00:11:13,640
seeing the forest for the trees.

173
00:11:14,540 --> 00:11:17,843
This idea that when you're in the middle of development,

174
00:11:17,883 --> 00:11:18,883
you're right in the thick of it,

175
00:11:19,404 --> 00:11:22,346
and you need to be able to back away a little bit

176
00:11:22,506 --> 00:11:23,927
and see the whole picture.

177
00:11:23,947 --> 00:11:26,189
And the only way that you can get that distance

178
00:11:26,209 --> 00:11:26,769
is with time.

179
00:11:29,171 --> 00:11:30,932
And then that last little bit is that

180
00:11:31,673 --> 00:11:35,375
you have to get some understanding of your situation

181
00:11:35,395 --> 00:11:36,516
in order to be able to assess it.

