because there's a lot of good and bad

242
00:16:38,712 --> 00:16:39,452
that can come with that.

243
00:16:40,472 --> 00:16:41,832
Anyway, sorry, I hope that addressed your question.

244
00:16:41,912 --> 00:16:42,573
Cheers.

245
00:16:42,793 --> 00:16:44,553
Thank you for your patience, everyone.

246
00:16:44,573 --> 00:16:45,874
Hi.

247
00:16:46,074 --> 00:16:49,114
Yeah, you, good answer.

248
00:16:49,355 --> 00:16:49,555
Yes.

249
00:16:51,400 --> 00:16:54,743
All right, so I'm going to talk about the Moonhunters mistake.

250
00:16:55,844 --> 00:16:58,106
You might know me as the captain of Kit Fox Games.

251
00:16:58,547 --> 00:17:00,749
Moonhunters was our biggest project, probably,

252
00:17:00,769 --> 00:17:01,790
in press so far.

253
00:17:02,230 --> 00:17:03,992
We also released A Shrouded Isle last year.

254
00:17:04,653 --> 00:17:07,155
And we just announced Boyfriend Dungeon.

255
00:17:07,175 --> 00:17:07,235
Woo!

256
00:17:08,857 --> 00:17:10,739
And I'm co-editing textbooks on the side.

257
00:17:11,820 --> 00:17:14,482
But it seems like most indies that get press and attention,

258
00:17:15,163 --> 00:17:20,367
appear to err on the side of waiting too long to release their games, extending their launch

259
00:17:20,407 --> 00:17:24,711
date again and again for years and years, and if that's right for you, that's fine,

260
00:17:24,751 --> 00:17:26,032
and we're all different people.

261
00:17:26,773 --> 00:17:27,874
Some people have that flaw.

262
00:17:28,054 --> 00:17:34,300
My flaw is the other side of the coin, and I know that I need to worry about not launching

263
00:17:34,400 --> 00:17:36,682
too early, because that's what we did.

264
00:17:37,862 --> 00:17:41,023
Luckily, now I know the warning signs that I'm ready to share with you.

265
00:17:42,324 --> 00:17:45,005
And this was 100% my call to make.

266
00:17:45,305 --> 00:17:50,546
I want to emphasize that my team was incredible and they gave me all the power to make this

267
00:17:50,586 --> 00:17:52,147
decision and I made it badly.

268
00:17:52,587 --> 00:17:54,347
So here I am.

269
00:17:54,427 --> 00:17:55,248
I called it wrong.

270
00:17:56,328 --> 00:18:00,511
Back in early 2016, we were getting ready to launch our biggest game.

271
00:18:01,432 --> 00:18:03,293
Moon Hunters was very exciting for us.

272
00:18:03,333 --> 00:18:06,135
We'd been working on it for only a little over two years.

273
00:18:06,455 --> 00:18:07,976
So it was ripe and ready.

274
00:18:08,576 --> 00:18:13,440
And we'd done a lot of promotion throughout the years in Montreal, at events, at PAX,

275
00:18:13,500 --> 00:18:16,102
and online with weekly live streams.

276
00:18:16,842 --> 00:18:20,104
We basically felt like we were living in this giant hot spotlight.

277
00:18:20,905 --> 00:18:23,066
And we had had a successful Kickstarter.

278
00:18:23,927 --> 00:18:26,169
$178,000 isn't like breaking any records,

279
00:18:26,249 --> 00:18:29,632
but for a first major game and a new IP from a new studio,

280
00:18:29,652 --> 00:18:33,736
I mean, 400% and 6,000 backers was very exciting

281
00:18:33,756 --> 00:18:34,737
and something to be proud of.

282
00:18:35,397 --> 00:18:37,579
And I mean, we didn't even have a mid-campaign slump.

283
00:18:38,220 --> 00:18:41,182
It seemed like it had its own word of mouth power.

284
00:18:41,262 --> 00:18:44,065
It would somehow organically grow out there on the internet.

285
00:18:44,725 --> 00:18:46,947
And in the years following, I gave lots of talks

286
00:18:47,007 --> 00:18:49,049
about how to run a successful Kickstarter.

287
00:18:50,030 --> 00:18:54,614
Haha, and I mean all this coverage and word-of-mouth

288
00:18:55,054 --> 00:19:00,619
It seemed like it was paying off. We got into showcases. We won awards. We were on the covers of magazines

289
00:19:00,679 --> 00:19:03,862
I mean we were bombarded with publishing offers, which we discarded

290
00:19:03,882 --> 00:19:07,705
And so I mean we we got a little bit cocky

291
00:19:07,725 --> 00:19:11,828
It was reasonable to think that it was a good sign of sales to come

292
00:19:12,509 --> 00:19:16,692
Everyone that I talked to told me we had a hit on our hands

293
00:19:17,753 --> 00:19:24,059
We actually launched with months of cash in the bank and a contract that was ready to sign.

294
00:19:24,259 --> 00:19:28,443
We had no financial pressure to launch at all and yet we still launched early.

295
00:19:29,204 --> 00:19:35,409
In fact, we had so much visibility and so much good fortune that our launch moment was filmed by a crew from PBS

296
00:19:35,589 --> 00:19:39,193
for a TV series on tech and culture, which we'll come back in a moment.

297
00:19:40,833 --> 00:19:45,296
The launch was bad, I don't know if you've gotten that from what I've said so far, but

298
00:19:45,577 --> 00:19:46,878
we disappointed our fans.

299
00:19:47,978 --> 00:19:53,142
You can't please everyone, of course, but we did have to admit to ourselves that we'd

300
00:19:53,182 --> 00:19:58,426
launched with a lot of bugs and maybe, well, definitely worse, a few core systems that

301
00:19:58,446 --> 00:20:00,207
we felt needed serious changes.

302
00:20:01,423 --> 00:20:03,845
So we ended up with a mixed Steam review user rating

303
00:20:04,286 --> 00:20:07,549
in the half, like on and off in the launch month,

304
00:20:07,890 --> 00:20:09,672
which kind of tanked our whole visibility.

305
00:20:10,452 --> 00:20:11,934
Metacritic was not much better.

306
00:20:11,954 --> 00:20:14,457
And I think, honestly, the hardest thing

307
00:20:14,657 --> 00:20:17,600
was seeing other devs, especially acquaintances,

308
00:20:17,620 --> 00:20:19,482
kind of treat me a little bit differently

309
00:20:19,902 --> 00:20:22,165
than they had back when they thought that I had a hit.

310
00:20:22,585 --> 00:20:24,267
And now that I didn't, it was different.

311
00:20:26,032 --> 00:20:31,076
And to make matters worse, mainstream audiences were already set up to doubt the game's integrity.

312
00:20:31,256 --> 00:20:34,738
I mean, of course, some of these people would never have bought the game, they weren't our audience,

313
00:20:35,179 --> 00:20:41,163
but it still kind of, like, was not fun to know that our technical problems would prove the indie skeptics right

314
00:20:41,604 --> 00:20:45,287
in calling us low-rent garbage. Like, that's not a good feeling either.

315
00:20:46,209 --> 00:20:48,390
And there were measurable consequences to this problem.

316
00:20:48,810 --> 00:20:51,230
This mistake cost us a lot.

317
00:20:51,550 --> 00:20:53,611
This is how you tell it's a healthy launch week, by the way.

318
00:20:54,011 --> 00:20:55,271
Our next launch went much better

319
00:20:55,331 --> 00:20:57,251
in terms of how the launch week went.

320
00:20:57,551 --> 00:20:59,952
So you can see, even if that peak is not as high,

321
00:21:00,372 --> 00:21:02,493
the fact that it's fatter throughout the days,

322
00:21:02,513 --> 00:21:04,293
this is just the first three days of the launch week,

323
00:21:05,073 --> 00:21:06,173
it means people who are buying it

324
00:21:06,213 --> 00:21:07,154
are telling their friends.

325
00:21:07,434 --> 00:21:09,594
That's a good launch week looking.

326
00:21:09,954 --> 00:21:16,843
as unlike Moon Hunters, which launched and the hype train hit this big wall.

327
00:21:18,084 --> 00:21:22,309
So you can see which one is going to have a better next four days, for example.

328
00:21:24,003 --> 00:21:25,603
I mean, launch days don't determine everything

329
00:21:25,643 --> 00:21:27,544
about your revenue, but it did determine

330
00:21:27,564 --> 00:21:29,724
a lot of the coverage and apparent success

331
00:21:29,924 --> 00:21:32,045
of the game for the next six months to a year.

332
00:21:32,645 --> 00:21:34,125
I can't help but think if that we'd waited

333
00:21:34,185 --> 00:21:36,786
to launch the game until it was actually ready,

334
00:21:37,266 --> 00:21:38,866
then our Metacritic and user reviews

335
00:21:38,886 --> 00:21:40,246
might have been much higher, and all of that

336
00:21:40,286 --> 00:21:42,527
would have led to even higher spikes down the road,

337
00:21:42,927 --> 00:21:44,307
which would have amounted to an additional

338
00:21:44,407 --> 00:21:46,228
hundreds of thousands of dollars.

339
00:21:48,266 --> 00:21:49,667
This is what PBS had to say.

340
00:21:50,447 --> 00:21:52,568
Sales weren't great, thanks PBS,

341
00:21:53,168 --> 00:21:55,129
but that's what happens when you release a game

342
00:21:55,169 --> 00:21:55,789
that isn't ready.

343
00:21:56,689 --> 00:21:58,630
And despite our launch day being better

344
00:21:58,710 --> 00:22:00,491
than a lot of indies, I'm very grateful

345
00:22:00,571 --> 00:22:02,632
for what luck we did have.

346
00:22:03,332 --> 00:22:04,873
We could tell that this coming year,

347
00:22:05,413 --> 00:22:07,834
we might not have enough money to stay in the studio

348
00:22:07,954 --> 00:22:09,515
at the size and the comfort level

349
00:22:09,595 --> 00:22:10,595
that we were getting used to.

350
00:22:11,850 --> 00:22:15,854
And even aside from the money, I prepared myself emotionally for bad sales.

351
00:22:16,254 --> 00:22:19,337
That's why I had signed this other contract beforehand.

352
00:22:19,457 --> 00:22:24,662
But I hadn't really considered seriously that we might disappoint people and make what

353
00:22:24,722 --> 00:22:26,424
could be called a bad game.

354
00:22:27,425 --> 00:22:28,245
We were heartbroken.

355
00:22:28,366 --> 00:22:32,209
It felt like we'd wasted years of our lives making something that wasn't really worth

356
00:22:32,329 --> 00:22:33,370
all that time and energy.

357
00:22:33,771 --> 00:22:36,814
It made me feel like I'd peaked and that I was old and tired.

358
00:22:37,928 --> 00:22:39,668
And in hindsight, we totally should have known better.

359
00:22:39,989 --> 00:22:42,449
One YouTuber went so far as to write me a heartfelt letter

360
00:22:42,509 --> 00:22:45,530
during the beta, pleading with me to delay the launch.

361
00:22:46,171 --> 00:22:48,871
But I ignored that and all the other warning signs

362
00:22:49,272 --> 00:22:50,772
because hindsight's so great.

363
00:22:52,093 --> 00:22:53,353
So why did we launch too early?

364
00:22:53,453 --> 00:22:55,294
If we set aside the hindsight bias

365
00:22:55,754 --> 00:22:56,934
and think about the moment,

366
00:22:57,474 --> 00:23:00,215
I'm gonna lay bare all of my personal flaws for you

367
00:23:00,235 --> 00:23:03,356
so that you can see if any of this sounds familiar,

368
00:23:03,716 --> 00:23:05,937
you might have a similar problem.

369
00:23:07,932 --> 00:23:11,953
Indies often go around saying you should double or triple all your estimates and then double

370
00:23:11,993 --> 00:23:16,494
them again and it makes me want to scream because production is actually a skill and

371
00:23:16,514 --> 00:23:17,575
it's worth practicing.

372
00:23:19,215 --> 00:23:22,997
And so I get a little bit defiant when people start telling me you're going to keep delaying

373
00:23:23,017 --> 00:23:23,377
your game.

374
00:23:23,717 --> 00:23:25,177
Ha ha ha, your launch date isn't real.

375
00:23:25,817 --> 00:23:27,978
In fact I got really like, fuck you, defiant.

376
00:23:29,659 --> 00:23:34,121
And it is totally possible to release your game on schedule, I promise.

377
00:23:34,861 --> 00:23:39,103
But don't give up everything and obsess on that, maybe?

378
00:23:41,087 --> 00:23:44,571
And so it came to pass that each delay that we added to the game,

379
00:23:44,671 --> 00:23:48,255
even like a week of delay, felt like a personal attack on me

380
00:23:48,896 --> 00:23:50,158
and my production skill.

381
00:23:50,758 --> 00:23:52,941
And I started feeling kind of fraudulent.

382
00:23:53,121 --> 00:23:56,545
And so I irrationally had decided we couldn't delay again.

383
00:23:56,585 --> 00:23:57,366
We just couldn't.

384
00:23:57,507 --> 00:24:00,490
It was a law of the universe now, which was incorrect.

385
00:24:01,792 --> 00:24:04,296
And the team morale was getting a little bit low,

386
00:24:04,416 --> 00:24:06,678
and I'm a cheerleader type personality,

387
00:24:06,859 --> 00:24:09,742
so we weren't crunching particularly.

388
00:24:09,822 --> 00:24:10,844
We were working pretty hard,

389
00:24:11,625 --> 00:24:13,247
and finishing projects is exhausting.

390
00:24:13,847 --> 00:24:15,429
Even if you only work 40 hours a week,

391
00:24:15,469 --> 00:24:17,772
you're multitasking, you're prioritizing, you're.

392
00:24:18,032 --> 00:24:23,537
you're compromising and just finishing a game is really difficult. So I was looking at the

393
00:24:23,557 --> 00:24:27,441
team and we'd already delayed by a few weeks and I thought well um you know I want I want

394
00:24:27,461 --> 00:24:33,005
them to be happy again let's release the game. Um but releasing a bad game does not make

395
00:24:33,065 --> 00:24:34,907
anyone happy it turns out.

396
00:24:37,509 --> 00:24:41,974
And I also worried about launching next to a couple of other indie games and during other

397
00:24:42,014 --> 00:24:44,157
game events like GDC and PAX and things.

398
00:24:44,317 --> 00:24:48,842
And in the greater scheme of things, I think there are actually much bigger things to worry

399
00:24:48,882 --> 00:24:49,062
about.

400
00:24:49,102 --> 00:24:53,507
The quality of your game is much more important than probably any other indie game, to be

401
00:24:53,547 --> 00:24:54,228
completely honest.

402
00:24:55,999 --> 00:24:57,800
And this might be very Moonhunter specific,

403
00:24:58,040 --> 00:25:00,302
but due to various factors,

404
00:25:00,342 --> 00:25:02,263
we undervalued the online multiplayer

405
00:25:02,383 --> 00:25:04,084
and we launched with it in a beta mode,

406
00:25:04,144 --> 00:25:04,964
which we thought was fine.

407
00:25:04,984 --> 00:25:05,965
We marked it beta.

408
00:25:07,046 --> 00:25:09,387
Still, most of the down thumbs

409
00:25:09,507 --> 00:25:11,688
were bad online multiplayer related

410
00:25:12,269 --> 00:25:13,789
and they would never revise those

411
00:25:13,849 --> 00:25:15,290
no matter how we pleaded with them

412
00:25:15,530 --> 00:25:16,691
after we fixed the bugs.

413
00:25:17,972 --> 00:25:19,273
And yeah, we thought it would be okay

414
00:25:19,313 --> 00:25:20,653
if the online multiplayer took a little while.

415
00:25:21,154 --> 00:25:21,814
That was incorrect.

416
00:25:24,267 --> 00:25:26,908
And as I mentioned, we had lined up this contract

417
00:25:26,928 --> 00:25:28,770
that was starting very soon afterwards,

418
00:25:29,310 --> 00:25:30,931
and I'd already delayed that by a few weeks,

419
00:25:30,991 --> 00:25:33,753
and so I let this external factor kind of influence me

420
00:25:34,393 --> 00:25:37,455
and make me think that we absolutely had

421
00:25:37,895 --> 00:25:40,637
to stop working on the game.

422
00:25:41,017 --> 00:25:42,258
And it's true that at that point,

423
00:25:42,298 --> 00:25:43,979
because I had scheduled this contract to start,

424
00:25:44,459 --> 00:25:47,661
if I had delayed again, it was theoretically possible that.

425
00:25:48,278 --> 00:25:52,946
the game would then sell zero copies and that contract would be null and void and then Kitfox

426
00:25:52,986 --> 00:25:53,547
would close.

427
00:25:54,209 --> 00:26:00,640
So it felt like the right thing at the time to prioritize this other external factor.

428
00:26:01,796 --> 00:26:02,997
And we did eventually do okay.

429
00:26:03,457 --> 00:26:04,198
Kid Fox survived.

430
00:26:04,598 --> 00:26:07,020
Moon Hunters actually did pretty well over time.

431
00:26:07,520 --> 00:26:09,601
Some of it is my personal excellent luck.

432
00:26:09,841 --> 00:26:10,742
I'm a very lucky person,

433
00:26:11,222 --> 00:26:12,423
and I try to stay grateful for that,

434
00:26:12,623 --> 00:26:14,605
but we also did work really hard at it.

435
00:26:15,085 --> 00:26:17,527
We spent a lot of time fixing bugs

436
00:26:17,567 --> 00:26:19,528
and apologizing and answering emails.

437
00:26:20,169 --> 00:26:24,291
We also spent about six months making a free DLC afterwards

438
00:26:24,651 --> 00:26:25,592
called Eternal Echoes.

439
00:26:25,832 --> 00:26:28,034
And that did the core systems revising

440
00:26:28,094 --> 00:26:28,914
that I mentioned before.

441
00:26:29,895 --> 00:26:31,736
And so that gave us kind of another attempt

442
00:26:31,936 --> 00:26:32,957
at attracting press.

443
00:26:33,517 --> 00:26:35,418
And it gave us more of a peace of mind

444
00:26:35,759 --> 00:26:37,560
as well to leave the game in a better state

445
00:26:37,600 --> 00:26:38,380
that we were proud of.

446
00:26:38,620 --> 00:26:41,102
So even if it hadn't resulted in a sales boost,

447
00:26:41,162 --> 00:26:42,683
we still would have been glad that we did it.

448
00:26:43,944 --> 00:26:46,286
And also, making this would have been so much faster

449
00:26:46,346 --> 00:26:46,946
before launch.

450
00:26:47,787 --> 00:26:49,268
If you have something you want to add to the game

451
00:26:49,668 --> 00:26:51,290
and you can afford to delay it,

452
00:26:51,370 --> 00:26:52,791
just put it in the game first

453
00:26:52,871 --> 00:26:55,533
because LiveOps is horrendously distracting.

454
00:26:56,814 --> 00:26:59,015
And the reviews did trend mostly upwards afterwards.

455
00:26:59,216 --> 00:27:00,637
After we made all those improvements,

456
00:27:01,057 --> 00:27:03,379
I think we actually were able to harvest the goodwill

457
00:27:03,419 --> 00:27:05,380
that we'd built up from the Kickstarter updates

458
00:27:05,400 --> 00:27:06,361
that we were constantly making.

459
00:27:06,381 --> 00:27:08,383
And maybe our community is more forgiving

460
00:27:08,403 --> 00:27:09,463
than the average Steam player.

461
00:27:10,024 --> 00:27:10,704
I guess we'll never know.

462
00:27:12,084 --> 00:27:16,467
One thing that I do want to emphasize is the importance of our launch party, actually.

463
00:27:16,967 --> 00:27:21,590
My team and I definitely felt like we received first aid from the Montreal community itself

464
00:27:22,270 --> 00:27:24,191
by hosting our launch party three days later.

465
00:27:24,211 --> 00:27:29,835
There's nothing that can replace the feeling of people who genuinely are happy for you

466
00:27:30,415 --> 00:27:33,056
and being proud of you and excited for you.

467
00:27:33,657 --> 00:27:36,998
Everyone on the team kind of wanted to cancel the launch party.

468
00:27:38,299 --> 00:27:40,700
But we did it anyway, and we were all really,

469
00:27:40,840 --> 00:27:43,101
everybody on the team was also grateful that we did afterwards.

470
00:27:43,501 --> 00:27:45,822
There were sad tears and then happy tears.

471
00:27:46,823 --> 00:27:49,224
So if you're thinking about cancelling your launch party

472
00:27:49,324 --> 00:27:52,105
or making it hinge on the success of the game, do not do that.

473
00:27:52,685 --> 00:27:55,026
Even if you have to make it BYOB, that's okay.

474
00:27:55,467 --> 00:27:59,248
But take your moment to celebrate that you did something.

475
00:28:00,842 --> 00:28:03,524
And personally, I was actually healed by coming to GDC

476
00:28:03,564 --> 00:28:04,686
the week after launching.

477
00:28:05,106 --> 00:28:06,708
I thought it would be massively humiliating,

478
00:28:07,528 --> 00:28:09,070
and instead it was comforting.

479
00:28:09,871 --> 00:28:11,332
Even though a few professional acquaintances

480
00:28:11,372 --> 00:28:12,573
did treat me a little bit differently,

481
00:28:13,414 --> 00:28:15,737
I did actually find out who my friends were

482
00:28:15,817 --> 00:28:19,300
among the community who could share with me

483
00:28:19,400 --> 00:28:21,042
their experiences from around the world.

484
00:28:22,343 --> 00:28:24,544
Because whenever I told someone about my disappointment,

485
00:28:24,984 --> 00:28:28,105
more experienced indies would lean in and nod sagely

486
00:28:28,205 --> 00:28:30,946
and tell me a horror story that was way worse,

487
00:28:31,986 --> 00:28:33,447
which I'd never heard of.

488
00:28:33,467 --> 00:28:36,488
Like, we only talk about success.

489
00:28:36,508 --> 00:28:37,968
I mean, all I say in public is,

490
00:28:38,008 --> 00:28:39,609
Moon Hunter is totally successful.

491
00:28:39,729 --> 00:28:40,929
Yeah, it was great.

492
00:28:41,829 --> 00:28:43,410
But for those of you who are in the audience right now,

493
00:28:43,470 --> 00:28:46,551
please understand that games go off the tracks all the time.

494
00:28:47,091 --> 00:28:49,232
It's okay, you're not uniquely humiliated.

495
00:28:50,692 --> 00:28:51,933
It's kind of part of it.

496
00:28:52,794 --> 00:28:54,555
So that's part of why I volunteered to be here today,

497
00:28:54,615 --> 00:28:57,177
because I not only want to combat survivorship bias,

498
00:28:57,237 --> 00:28:59,259
but generally improve our culture

499
00:28:59,779 --> 00:29:01,561
and help us understand that failure

500
00:29:01,641 --> 00:29:02,681
is part of craftsmanship.

501
00:29:04,244 --> 00:29:06,065
And all that visibility that we'd created before

502
00:29:06,105 --> 00:29:07,086
didn't vaporize.

503
00:29:07,727 --> 00:29:09,147
I was able to do some hustling

