516
00:29:35,724 --> 00:29:37,045
our Steam sales would get a boost.

517
00:29:37,925 --> 00:29:40,726
And I think that if we had simultaneously launched

518
00:29:40,906 --> 00:29:42,547
all of the games on all the platforms,

519
00:29:42,587 --> 00:29:44,048
which is the conventional wisdom,

520
00:29:44,068 --> 00:29:45,709
well, we couldn't have done that physically anyway.

521
00:29:45,749 --> 00:29:46,409
We were incapable.

522
00:29:46,469 --> 00:29:49,330
But even if we had, I think the Halo effect

523
00:29:49,351 --> 00:29:50,691
would have been kind of negated by the fact

524
00:29:50,711 --> 00:29:52,032
that our Steam score was so low.

525
00:29:52,532 --> 00:29:54,333
So it was really good that we were able to

526
00:29:54,433 --> 00:29:56,694
put the best version on the platform after we had...

527
00:29:57,121 --> 00:29:58,242
kind of salvaged that.

528
00:29:59,763 --> 00:30:01,365
And most importantly to the future of the studio,

529
00:30:01,565 --> 00:30:03,287
we've incorporated all of these lessons

530
00:30:03,367 --> 00:30:04,888
into our workflows going forward.

531
00:30:04,908 --> 00:30:06,870
So our production evaluations for milestones

532
00:30:07,351 --> 00:30:09,353
are now less about specific dates

533
00:30:09,613 --> 00:30:12,756
and much more about what the deliveries themselves are

534
00:30:12,796 --> 00:30:14,077
and whether they are up to par.

535
00:30:14,577 --> 00:30:17,680
So we're more willing to add some time to the schedule

536
00:30:17,700 --> 00:30:21,984
as assuming that everything is up to quality.

537
00:30:22,744 --> 00:30:25,426
And survival of the studio is definitely number one still in my mind.

538
00:30:26,027 --> 00:30:27,448
Kit Fox is not allowed to close.

539
00:30:27,929 --> 00:30:30,511
But in the past we failed to prioritize beyond that.

540
00:30:30,611 --> 00:30:34,035
So my own personal production neuroses would come through.

541
00:30:34,055 --> 00:30:36,978
And kind of efficiency became more important than quality.

542
00:30:37,939 --> 00:30:41,122
And that was by accident because we didn't really examine it.

543
00:30:41,242 --> 00:30:44,325
So now we're very clearly, officially...

544
00:30:44,845 --> 00:30:46,686
Quality is more important than efficiency,

545
00:30:47,306 --> 00:30:49,126
so assuming that you're not gonna close the studio

546
00:30:49,186 --> 00:30:51,847
with your little flares here and there,

547
00:30:51,927 --> 00:30:54,747
then take your time and make it the best you can.

548
00:30:55,467 --> 00:30:57,968
Because it's true what they say, you do only launch once.

549
00:30:58,668 --> 00:31:00,468
Delaying your game isn't nearly as bad

550
00:31:00,728 --> 00:31:02,269
as launching a bad game.

551
00:31:03,869 --> 00:31:06,749
Reality is probably more important than your pride.

552
00:31:07,349 --> 00:31:08,730
Your team's morale will be better

553
00:31:08,810 --> 00:31:10,010
when they believe in the game

554
00:31:10,150 --> 00:31:11,730
and feel good about what they've made.

555
00:31:12,210 --> 00:31:14,132
So if you're like me and you're prone to rushing ahead

556
00:31:14,152 --> 00:31:15,313
and you're an impatient person,

557
00:31:15,973 --> 00:31:17,914
just take a breath, recheck your calculations,

558
00:31:17,974 --> 00:31:20,937
bring in fresh eyes, double check all of your assumptions.

559
00:31:21,557 --> 00:31:22,958
We're applying all of this to development

560
00:31:22,998 --> 00:31:24,619
of Boyfriend Dungeon, which is our next game,

561
00:31:24,719 --> 00:31:25,680
so wish us luck with that.

562
00:31:25,700 --> 00:31:29,583
We actually have a milestone next week, so we'll see.

563
00:31:29,743 --> 00:31:31,324
And hopefully we're learning from our mistakes

564
00:31:31,624 --> 00:31:33,165
and making better and better games.

565
00:31:33,646 --> 00:31:33,926
Thank you.

