00:32:05,989 --> 00:32:06,249
Hello.

573
00:32:06,269 --> 00:32:06,809
Hi.

574
00:32:06,829 --> 00:32:07,410
How's it going?

575
00:32:07,810 --> 00:32:08,570
It's excellent.

576
00:32:09,130 --> 00:32:10,531
This question's for you primarily.

577
00:32:11,872 --> 00:32:12,932
I've had the experience where I've

578
00:32:12,972 --> 00:32:15,253
had friends who have metaphorically grabbed me

579
00:32:15,273 --> 00:32:17,094
by the shoulders and shaken me and saying,

580
00:32:17,394 --> 00:32:18,635
you need to finish.

581
00:32:18,715 --> 00:32:20,255
Finishing is super important.

582
00:32:20,775 --> 00:32:22,896
And don't just stay in development forever

583
00:32:23,417 --> 00:32:27,338
and almost yell at me to move forward.

584
00:32:28,299 --> 00:32:29,979
Outside of actual financial pressure,

585
00:32:30,199 --> 00:32:32,100
you're going to close if you don't start releasing something.

586
00:32:33,241 --> 00:32:34,641
How would you respond to that?

587
00:32:35,360 --> 00:32:37,880
I would say I am probably unusual.

588
00:32:38,100 --> 00:32:43,021
It does seem to me that I am an outlier and that most people err on the other side.

589
00:32:43,642 --> 00:32:48,643
Like I said at the beginning, I think most indies tend towards just working in a cave

590
00:32:48,703 --> 00:32:53,964
forever on their perfect dream, whereas I am much more of a flurry of like, let's just

591
00:32:54,164 --> 00:32:54,544
do it.

592
00:32:55,644 --> 00:33:00,806
And so you have to look inside yourself to see what is your nature and how do you prevent

593
00:33:00,846 --> 00:33:04,907
that from calcifying because on both ends of the spectrum there are problems.

594
00:33:05,567 --> 00:33:08,169
And I guess my, I feel like my side of the spectrum

595
00:33:08,189 --> 00:33:09,650
isn't talked about as much.

596
00:33:10,070 --> 00:33:12,532
It's just seen as obvious, whereas sitting in a room

597
00:33:12,572 --> 00:33:14,053
and working on it for way too long

598
00:33:14,173 --> 00:33:15,094
is less obvious somehow.

599
00:33:16,695 --> 00:33:20,778
But yeah, I can't answer for you in particular.

600
00:33:20,898 --> 00:33:22,760
Only you can know your heart.

601
00:33:24,521 --> 00:33:28,084
But I would say that finishing is important.

602
00:33:28,304 --> 00:33:30,285
Maybe look up production practices.

603
00:33:30,466 --> 00:33:33,008
I think if we all started being more hygienic

604
00:33:33,108 --> 00:33:34,929
about how we estimate our tasks.

605
00:33:35,369 --> 00:33:37,731
and think about how long things actually take us

606
00:33:37,871 --> 00:33:40,194
and calculate that and check our assumptions

607
00:33:40,494 --> 00:33:42,997
on our timelines, then we'll all be happier.

608
00:33:44,258 --> 00:33:45,159
If I could chip in on that.

609
00:33:45,719 --> 00:33:48,660
The, one of the biggest changes that we've seen in the industry

610
00:33:48,680 --> 00:33:53,202
in the last 20 years is the fact that I think the vast majority

611
00:33:53,222 --> 00:33:54,922
of us in this room when we're shipping a game,

612
00:33:54,962 --> 00:33:56,383
we're shipping purely digitally, right?

613
00:33:57,983 --> 00:33:59,504
And that, the environment

614
00:33:59,544 --> 00:34:01,864
for shipping a game has totally changed, right?

615
00:34:01,984 --> 00:34:06,066
So you've got options for early access, you can just get

616
00:34:06,106 --> 00:34:07,066
on Steam for 100 bucks now.

617
00:34:08,066 --> 00:34:13,368
You can also do various forms of closed beta or closed alpha,

618
00:34:13,468 --> 00:34:14,588
look at spy party.

619
00:34:15,163 --> 00:34:20,525
look at Saltzman's Overland, what was the...

620
00:34:20,685 --> 00:34:22,965
Venge's current game, Overland.

621
00:34:23,806 --> 00:34:26,707
There's a lot of different ways that you can basically

622
00:34:26,887 --> 00:34:29,428
get the kind of feedback you need from a player base

623
00:34:30,928 --> 00:34:33,689
and keep it to only the diehards to figure out

624
00:34:33,909 --> 00:34:35,049
are we ready to ship or not?

625
00:34:35,169 --> 00:34:36,470
Because if you've got a bunch of people,

626
00:34:37,050 --> 00:34:38,571
the people who would love you screaming.

627
00:34:40,071 --> 00:34:41,452
then it's like, okay, maybe we should delay it.

628
00:34:41,492 --> 00:34:42,833
But otherwise, if everyone's like, thumbs up,

629
00:34:42,853 --> 00:34:46,476
then yeah, you can get a degree of external evaluation

630
00:34:46,556 --> 00:34:49,739
from people who don't have an influence on that.

631
00:34:50,299 --> 00:34:51,700
One thing I would mention is actually,

632
00:34:52,301 --> 00:34:54,963
there are part-time producers that you can hire out there.

633
00:34:55,063 --> 00:34:56,424
Felix Kramer's incredible.

634
00:34:56,804 --> 00:34:58,605
There's a bunch of part-time producers

635
00:34:58,625 --> 00:35:00,026
that you should totally think about

636
00:35:00,067 --> 00:35:01,428
throwing a couple hundred dollars on

637
00:35:01,468 --> 00:35:04,790
because it's probably worth it to get a real professional

638
00:35:04,850 --> 00:35:07,232
to look at your timeline and look at your game

639
00:35:07,672 --> 00:35:09,033
and give you an expert.

640
00:35:09,568 --> 00:35:11,608
assessment of whether or not you're ready to ship.

641
00:35:12,509 --> 00:35:12,929
Thank you both.

642
00:35:13,369 --> 00:35:13,529
Cheers.

643
00:35:13,549 --> 00:35:13,849
You're welcome.

